","Lacrimal artery","Supraorbital artery","Central retinal artery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraorbital artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a terminal branch of the ophthalmic artery that exits the orbit through the supraorbital notch to supply the forehead and anterior scalp.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other branches have different distributions. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior ethmoidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the posterior ethmoidal air cells and small portion of the nasal cavity. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior ethmoidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the anterior ethmoidal air cells, anterior meninges, and lateral nasal wall. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the lacrimal gland and adjacent conjunctiva. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the retina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The supraorbital artery is a terminal branch of the ophthalmic artery that supplies the forehead and scalp.","The ophthalmic artery enters the orbit through the optic canal alongside the optic nerve and gives multiple branches to supply orbital and periorbital structures."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Bird B, Stawicki SP. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Ophthalmic Arteries. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29493942","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"